label="Heading" data-key="heading" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1701771875509" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-heading" data-ver="1" data-id="1701771875509"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-center gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs gf-elm-left-lg" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><h2 class="gf_gs-text-heading-2">Lifting straps: General characteristics, main types</h2></div></div><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1701771875505" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1701771875505"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-xs gf_gs-text-paragraph-1" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><p>It’s hard to imagine weightlifting, powerlifting, and strength training in general without lifting straps. They come in all kinds of types and sizes, and each of them is designed specifically to cater to a different technique, exercise, and, of course, preference. Let’s see what the main types are and what are their main characteristics.&nbsp;</p></div></div><div data-label="Image" data-key="image" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1702040391342" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-image" data-ver="1.0" data-id="1702040391342" data-resolution="3000x3000"><div class="elm gf-elm-center gf_elm-left-xs gf-elm-center-lg gf-elm-center-md gf-elm-center-sm gf-elm-center-xs" data-exc=""><img src="https://ucarecdn.com/790a75f0-d8d5-4ade-b06d-e59f24a46f67/-/format/auto/-/preview/3000x3000/-/quality/lighter/Lifting%20straps_1.png" alt="" class="gf_image" data-gemlang="en" width="1200" height="800" data-width="100%" data-height="auto" title="" natural-width="1200" natural-height="800"></div></div><div data-label="Heading" data-key="heading" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1701771875690" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-heading" data-ver="2" data-id="1701771875690"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-center gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-xs" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><h3 class="gf_gs-text-heading-2"><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">1. Lasso</span></h3></div></div><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1701771875511" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1701771875511" style="display: block;"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs gf_gs-text-paragraph-1 gf-elm-left-lg" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><p>These feature a looped design that goes around the wrist and then wraps around the bar or weight. They provide a secure grip on the bar and are mostly used for deadlifts, rows, and various pulling exercises. Lasso straps help with maintaining grip strength during high-intensity workouts.&nbsp;</p></div></div><div data-label="Image" data-key="image" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1701847620148" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-image" data-ver="1.0" data-id="1701847620148" data-resolution="3000x3000"><div class="elm gf-elm-center gf_elm-left-xs gf-elm-center-lg gf-elm-center-md gf-elm-center-sm gf-elm-center-xs" data-exc=""><img src="https://ucarecdn.com/7626e784-75d7-409c-8fc7-98088750582c/-/format/auto/-/preview/3000x3000/-/quality/lighter/lasso-lifting-straps-torokhtiy.jpg" alt="Lasso straps" class="gf_image" data-gemlang="en" data-width="100%" data-height="auto" title="Lasso straps" width="3000" height="2000" natural-width="3000" natural-height="2000"></div></div><div data-label="Heading" data-key="heading" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1701771875692" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-heading" data-ver="2" data-id="1701771875692" style=""><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-center gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-xs" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><h3 class="gf_gs-text-heading-2"><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">2. Closed Loop (Olympic)</span></h3></div></div><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1701771875516" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1701771875516" style="display: block;"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-xs gf_gs-text-paragraph-1" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><p>Closed loop straps, also known as Olympic straps, form a teardrop shape  that encircles the wrist and then loops around the bar. Like the name would suggest, they’re designed for Olympic weightlifting, cleans, and snatches. The closed loop offers excellent support for quick movements and explosive lifts, so it allows you to focus on your technique without worrying about the strength of your grip.</p></div></div><div data-label="Image" data-key="image" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1701847873351" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-image" data-ver="1.0" data-id="1701847873351" data-resolution="3000x3000"><div class="elm gf-elm-center gf_elm-left-xs gf-elm-center-md gf-elm-center-sm gf-elm-center-xs gf-elm-center-lg" data-exc=""><img src="https://ucarecdn.com/116a4c92-0d35-4d70-b8f7-ce60aae1fee4/-/format/auto/-/preview/3000x3000/-/quality/lighter/Olympic-Lifting-Straps-Closed-Loop.webp" alt="closed loop straps" class="gf_image" data-gemlang="en" width="1920" height="1280" data-width="100%" data-height="auto" title="closed loop straps" natural-width="1920" natural-height="1280"></div></div><div data-label="Heading" data-key="heading" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1701771875694" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-heading" data-ver="2" data-id="1701771875694" style=""><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-center gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-xs" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><h3 class="gf_gs-text-heading-2"><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">3. Open Loop</span></h3></div></div><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1701771875514" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1701771875514" s